nd resources across the Colorado Plateau. Erika Marie Bsumek reorients the story of the dam to reveal a pattern of Indigenous erasure by weaving together the stories of religious settlers and Indigenous peoples, engineers and biologists, and politicians and spiritual leaders. Infrastructures of dispossession teach us that we cannot tell the stories of religious colonization, scientific exploration, regional engineering, environmental transformation, or political deal-making as disconnected from Indigenous history. This book is a provocative and essential piece of modern history, particularly as water in the West becomes increasingly scarce and fights over access to it continue to unfold.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIndians of North AmericazColorado PlateauxSocial conditionsxHistory. 0aSettler colonialismzColorado PlateauxHistory. 0aWater resources developmentxSocial aspectszColorado PlateauxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aSettler colonialism, Native American, Navajo, Diné, Water, Glen Canyon Dam, environmental history, Lake Powell, Indigenous, history of science, history of technology, history of the U.S. West, ecology, dispossession, infrastructure, dam, race, Mormon.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831107978240 cprintz978147730381840uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/30381840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97814773265894